			<mdl:MaterialGrid textAlign="LEFT">
				<mdl:MaterialLabel
					text="The Material Design Lite (MDL) grid component is a simplified method 
					for laying out content for multiple screen sizes. It reduces the usual coding 
					burden required to correctly display blocks of content in a 
					variety of display conditions."
					/>
				
				<mdl:MaterialLabel marginTop="16"
					text="
						The MDL grid is defined and enclosed by a container element. 
						A grid has 12 columns in the desktop screen size, 
						8 in the tablet size, and 4 in the phone size, 
						each size having predefined margins and gutters. 
						Cells are laid out sequentially in a row, in the order they are defined, 
						with some exceptions:
					"/>
				
				<mdl:MaterialLabel marginLeft="32"
					text="
						If a cell doesn't fit in the row in one of the screen sizes, 
						it flows into the following line.
						" />
				
				<mdl:MaterialLabel marginLeft="32"
					text="
						If a cell has a specified column size equal to or larger than the number 
						of columns for the current screen size, it takes up the entirety of its row.
					"/>
				
				<mdl:MaterialLabel marginTop="16"
					text="You can set a maximum grid width, after which the grid stays centered
					 with padding on either side, by setting its max-width CSS property."
					 />
				
				<mdl:MaterialLabel marginTop="16"
					text="Grids are a fairly new and non-standardized feature in most user interfaces, 
						and provide users with a way to view content in an organized manner that might 
						otherwise be difficult to understand or retain. 
						Their design and use is an important factor in the overall user experience."
					 />
				
			</mdl:MaterialGrid>

